ge blocks of time for raiding.  It really takes work and dedication to be able to participate in a helpful way against most of the high end encounters and zones.  Leaving early every time and coming late to a raid really reduces your contribution and sometimes is more harmful to the overall raid than if you never showed up in the first place.<br><br>If you are looking for a guild that does a lot of raiding, then you should look at the raid board and the IGB rotation board and see who is regularly raiding mobs/zones that you are interested in.  I'm pretty sure you don't care if some low level guild is oriented to raiding and raids Crushbone or Cazic Thule every day, though as they level they might be a guild to watch.  Get the guild names and visit their websites if they have them to look at their charter and rules to make sure that you don't disagree with anything in them.<br><br>Then you really should try to group in regular dungeon/exp groups with many of the guild members of the guilds you have decided that you are interested in to get a feel of their members.  As an enchanter it shouldn't be hard to go on a few raids with the guilds either to get a feel of their raiding setup (tacticly organized, tacticly disorganized, planned well in advanced, ad hoc raids, etc).  If you haven't found any friction in their member base as a whole and like their play/raid style at that point, get a trial membership.  Then you can see what the /guildchat about all day, read their members only boards and start grouping/raiding with them seriously.  Don't complain about loot or complain that total strangers who are in the guild didn't drop whatever they were doing to do your epic/port you/res you/powerlevel you.  Heck, don't complain/whine about it in general.  Complaining/whining about a guild is a right you earn by actually being in the guild for a while, even then it isn't encouraged.  If you don't like something in a guild and have been there for a while, instead of complaining/whining about it, you should be trying to fix it.<br><br>If you want something and the guild isn't providing it, speak to the guild leadership and ask about it.  If what you want from a guild isn't happening and the officers haven't explained the situation to you suitably (most guilds don't put trial clerics up for Ragefire, Dragon scales usually don't go to trial warriors/bards, if you just joined an hour ago people probably aren't going to organize to take down Brother Qwinn the same night, etc) then the guild probably isn't for you.<br><br>If you are in a trial membership and decide that the guild is not for you, then simply be polite about it and to post on their board or tell their guild officers/leader that you felt that the guild wasn't the guild for you and leave.  This generally doesn't cause any hard feelings.<br><br>The only guild jumpers that people don't like are the ones who get a guild trial membership, complain about loot distribution, complain about lack of help with their epic, complain that they don't get into exp groups immediately, complain that the porters of the guild didn't port them from North Ro to West Freeport when they were in Kael, complain that the guild cleric didn't leave the crypt in seb to go find your bod and res you on the moon, etc, then drop from the guild without telling anyone and join another guild and do the same thing there.<br><br>Without knowing more about what you are looking for in a guild aside from loot/raid (what type of loot, what sort of raids) and what you want to/can put into the guild, no one can really make a good recomendation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/ufallainadreamchylde.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fallaina Dreamchylde</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.mmogamers.com/cadga/img/ikonboard/emoticons/bunny.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><